name: 04 - Model Training and Evaluation
content:
Model Training and Validation

Model Used:

  • Primary: H2O Distributed Random Forest (DRF) – chosen for its ability to handle large datasets, mixed feature types, and imbalanced classification problems.
  • Alternatives Tested: Logistic Regression (baseline), Gradient Boosting Trees, Neural Networks.

Features Used:

  • Key predictors:
  • intl_plan, voice_mail_plan, number_customer_service_calls.
  • total_day_minutes, total_eve_minutes, total_night_minutes.
  • total_intl_minutes, total_charges, account_length.
  • Derived Features:
  • domestic_usage, account_length_groups.

Feature Importance:

  • Determined using Gini importance from the Random Forest model.
  • Typically, the most important features are:
  • number_customer_service_calls.
  • intl_plan.
  • total_day_minutes and total_charges.

Model Metrics:

  • Accuracy – Overall correctness of predictions.
  • Precision – Proportion of correctly identified churners among predicted churners.
  • Recall (Sensitivity) – Ability to correctly capture actual churners (critical for retention).
  • F1 Score – Balance between precision and recall.
  • ROC-AUC – Ability to separate churn vs. non-churn customers.

Validation Strategy:

  • Train/test split (e.g., 80/20).
  • Cross-validation to ensure stability.
  • Confusion matrix to measure false positives (mislabeling loyal customers) and false negatives (missing churners).
